109|title=BrOTHERHOOD (Original Soundtrack) / Various Artists|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2016\n| {{n/a|None}}\n| ''[[Brotherhood (2016 film)|BrOTHERHOOD (Original Soundtrack)]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Lose Your Head\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/honey/1077033226|title=Honey by Katy B|website=iTunes|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Katy B]], TheHeavyTrackerz, D Double E\n| ''[[Honey (Katy B album)|Honey]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Liar Liar\" <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Remix)</span><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/liar-liar-ep/1166530100|title=Liar Liar \u2013 EP by Mostack|website=iTunes|accessdate=18 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409043254/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/liar-liar-ep/1166530100|archive-date=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Mostack, [[Krept & Konan]]\n| {{n/a|Non-album remix}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Bad Boys\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/gang-signs-prayer/1200527179|title=Gang Signs & Prayer by Stormzy|website=iTunes|accessdate=18 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402085714/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/gang-signs-prayer/1200527179|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2017\n| Stormzy, Ghetts\n| ''Gang Signs & Prayer''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Dealers & Robbers\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/high-street-kid/1232576457|title=High Street Kid by Mostack|website=iTunes|accessdate=18 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404181549/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/high-street-kid/1232576457|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Mostack\n| ''High Street Kid''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Get a Stack\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/7-days/1277067895|title=7 Days by Krept & Konan|website=iTunes|accessdate=18 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129120437/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/7-days/1277067895|archive-date=29 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Krept & Konan\n| ''[[7 Days (mixtape)|7 Days]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"What Do You Mean?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/ignorance-is-bliss/1461492004|title=Ignorance Is Bliss by Skepta|website=iTunes|accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2019\n| [[Skepta]]\n| ''[[Ignorance Is Bliss (Skepta album)|Ignorance Is Bliss]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Stinking Rich\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/mostack-stacko-tracklist|title=Mostack unveils tracklist for 'Stacko'|website=GRM Daily|date=5 May 2019|accessdate=8 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508113237/http://grmdaily.com/mostack-stacko-tracklist|archive-date=8 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| MoStack, Dave\n| ''Stacko''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Feels\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-announces-tracklisting-special-guests-new-album-no-6-collaborators-project-2510718/amp|title=Ed Sheeran announces tracklisting and special guests for new album \u2018No.6 Collaborators Project\u2018|website=NME|date=18 June 2019|accessdate=18 June 2019|first=Rhian|last=Daly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620052538/https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-announces-tracklisting-special-guests-new-album-no-6-collaborators-project-2510718/amp|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Ed Sheeran, Young Thug\n| ''No.6 Collaborations Project''\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Organisation\n! Category\n! Award\n! Result\n|-\n|2017\n|[[Mercury Prize]]\n|''Common Sense''\n|Album Award\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n|[http://www.nme.com/news/music/winners-vo5-nme-awards-2018-2241619 VO5 NME Awards 2018] \n|Common Sense\n|Best Album (supported by Orange Amplification)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/winners-vo5-nme-awards-2018-2241619|title=Here are all the winners from the VO5 NME Awards 2018 \u2013 NME|date=14 February 2018|work=NME|access-date=27 February 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509174638/http://www.nme.com/news/music/winners-vo5-nme-awards-2018-2241619|archive-date=9 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|2018\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[2018 Brit Awards|Brit Awards]]\n|''Common Sense''\n|[[Brit Award for British Album of the Year|British Album of the Year]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\"Did You See\"\n|[[Brit Award for British Single of the Year|British Single of the Year]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|J Hus\n|[[Brit Award for British Breakthrough Act|British Breakthrough Act]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hus, J}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Gambian descent]]\n[[Category:Fula people]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n[[Category:People from Stratford, London]]\n[[Category:English male rappers]]\n[[Category:Black British male rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the British rapper and singer|the Czech theologian and reformer|Jan Hus}}\n{{short description|British rapper and pioneer of afroswing}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| image            = File:J Hus.png\n| name             = J Hus\n| background       = solo_singer\n| caption          = J Hus in January 2018\n| birth_name       = Momodou Lamin Jallow<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jarvis |first1=Jacob |title=Wireless Festival 2019: J Hus confirmed as replacement for ASAP Rocky at Finsbury Park after US rapper detained in Sweden |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/wireless-festival-2019-j-hus-confirmed-as-replacement-for-asap-rocky-at-finsbury-park-after-us-a4183876.html |website=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |date=6 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707131349/https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/wireless-festival-2019-j-hus-confirmed-as-replacement-for-asap-rocky-at-finsbury-park-after-us-a4183876.html |archive-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|1996|5|26}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/j-hus-mn0003446628|title=J Hus {{!}} Biography, Albums, Streaming Links|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=21 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322015646/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/j-hus-mn0003446628|archive-date=22 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| origin           = [[Stratford, London]], England\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[hip hop music|Hip hop]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thesource.com/tag/j-hus/|title=BRITISH MUSIC STAR J HUS, MIXING GRIME, HIP HOP AND AFRICAN SOUNDS AND TAKING IT WORLDWIDE|website=TheSource.com|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url= https://thesource.com/tag/j-hus/|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[afroswing]]\n* [[road rap]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 2014\u2013present\n| label            = [[Black Butter Records]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.jhusmusic.com}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Dave (rapper)|Dave]]\n* [[Burna Boy]]\n* [[Stormzy]] \n* [[Mist (rapper)|Mist]]\n*[[Skepta]]\n* [[Nines (rapper)|Nines]] }}\n}}\n'''Momodou Lamin Jallow''' (born 26 May 1996), better known professionally as '''J Hus''', is a British rapper, singer, songwriter and model. He is currently signed to [[Black Butter Records]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.musicweek.com/labels/read/j-hus-is-part-of-a-golden-age-for-the-uk-black-butter-president-joe-gossa-on-the-common-sense-campaign/069564|title='J Hus is part of a golden age for the UK': Black Butter president Joe Gossa on the Common Sense campaign|access-date=14 November 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115015101/http://www.musicweek.com/labels/read/j-hus-is-part-of-a-golden-age-for-the-uk-black-butter-president-joe-gossa-on-the-common-sense-campaign/069564|archive-date=15 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> J Hus has been credited with pioneering the genre [[afroswing]].<ref name=\"Mokoena\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/qvq9yb/afroswing-afrobeats-essay-industry|title=Afroswing Is More Than a Trend|last=Mokoena|first=Tshepo|last2=Bernard|first2=Jesse|date=2019-01-04|website=Vice|language=en-UK|access-date=2019-08-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722030037/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/qvq9yb/afroswing-afrobeats-essay-industry|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Mokoena\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/news/murking-it-j-hus|title=Murking It: J Hus|website=Clash Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-08-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808072835/https://www.clashmusic.com/news/murking-it-j-hus|archive-date=8 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808072732/https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/projects/best-uk-rappers-mcs-who-changed-the-game|title=Best UK rappers: 25 influential MCs that shaped UK Rap|date=2019-08-08|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref> He gained popularity in 2015 following the release of his song \"Dem Boy Paigon\".\n\nJ Hus's \"[[Did You See (song)|Did You See]]\" became his most successful single, peaking at number nine on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and eventually being certified [[BPI certification|Platinum]]. In 2017, he released his debut album, ''[[Common Sense (J Hus album)|Common Sense]]'', which was critical acclaimed \u2014 it was named the best UK album of 2017 by [[Complex (magazine)|''Complex'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/12/complex-uk-best-albums-of-2017/|title=Complex UK\u2019s Best Albums Of 2017|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> The album reached number six on the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/common-sense/id1220093029/ |title=Common Sense by J Hus on Apple Music \u2013 iTunes |publisher=iTunes |date=28 April 2017 |accessdate=28 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425115050/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/common-sense/id1220093029 |archive-date=25 April 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/05/12/stream-j-huss-debut-album-common-sense/ |title=Stream J Hus's debut album Common Sense |website=Factmag.com |date= |accessdate=17 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516003616/http://www.factmag.com/2017/05/12/stream-j-huss-debut-album-common-sense/ |archive-date=16 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2018, he was arrested in Stratford and charged with [[Knife legislation#United Kingdom|carrying a knife in public]].<ref name=\"newham recorder\" /> Hours after his release from prison in April 2019, he made a surprise appearance on stage at Canadian rapper [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]'s concert in London.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn January 2020, J Hus released his second album, ''[[Big Conspiracy]]'', which featured appearances by Jamaican singer [[Koffee (singer)|Koffee]], Nigerian singer [[Burna Boy]] and British singer [[Ella Mai]]. The album became his first number-one on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and received widespread critical acclaim.\n\n==Background==\nJ Hus was born Momodou Lamin Jallow in [[London]] and grew up in the city's [[Stratford, London|Stratford]] district. He is of [[The Gambia|Gambian]] and [[Ghana|Ghanaian]] descent and was raised by his mother, who emigrated to England when she was 25 years old.<ref name=\"fader2017\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/04/25/j-hus-fader-cover-story-interview-afrobeats |title=J Hus Is The Sound Of Diaspora\u2019s Boomerang |publisher=[[The Fader]] |date=25 April 2017 |accessdate=7 December 2017 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206072740/http://www.thefader.com/2017/04/25/j-hus-fader-cover-story-interview-afrobeats |archive-date=6 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Jallow was raised [[Muslim]] and is of ethnic [[Fula people|Fula]] and [[Ashanti people|Akan]] heritage.<ref name=\"TheGuardian\" /> Growing up he had wanted to become an actor \"but then around Year 10 or Year 11, it was whatever really\", and he was expelled from school as he had, in his words, \"started getting into a bit of trouble.\"<ref>{{citeweb |url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/53ndxk/j-hus-interview-2017-common-sense |title=No One Is Like J Hus |publisher=[[Noisey]] |date=12 May 2017 |accessdate=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107104241/https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/53ndxk/j-hus-interview-2017-common-sense |archive-date=7 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2014, distraught following two separate prison stints, he was advised to focus on pursuing a music career by his childhood friend Moe who also agreed to be his manager. Moe and his older brother would go on to form their own management company 2K Management.<ref name=\"fader2017\"/>\n\nJ Hus got his name from the word \"hustler\", explaining that he would buy a pack of doughnuts and sell them individually at a profit when he was in [[secondary school]].<ref name=\"TheGuardian\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/may/25/rapper-j-hus-i-was-doughnut-hustler-common-sense|title=Rapper J Hus: \u2018I was a doughnut hustler!\u2019|last=Yates|first=Kieran|date=25 May 2017|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=16 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218024023/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/may/25/rapper-j-hus-i-was-doughnut-hustler-common-sense|archive-date=18 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n===2015\u2013present: ''Common Sense'' and ''Big Conspiracy''===\nJ Hus began his career by recording several freestyles,<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> including #StreetHeat, Bl@CKBOX and [[GRM Daily]] <ref name=\"thelinkup\">{{cite web|url=http://thelinkup.com/why-jhus-is-a-rare-breed-of-sick-rapper-and-anthem-factory/|title=Why J Hus Is A Rare Breed Of Sick Rapper and Anthem Factory|publisher=Thelinkup.com|access-date=21 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322015919/http://thelinkup.com/why-jhus-is-a-rare-breed-of-sick-rapper-and-anthem-factory/|archive-date=22 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and publishing them online.<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> He followed this with \"#Rated\", which samples the beat from [[French Montana]]'s \"Don't Panic\", and \"Want From Me\" Remix of [[Kojo Funds]]' song, which gained a lot of coverage, helping his breakthrough. His next release was \"Dem Boy Paigon\", which was described by Ajay Rose of The Link Up as having \"brought together an Afro-beat sound with lyrical rap ... capable of turning any dance upside down\". He followed this with \"No Lie\" and his Warm Up. Session.<ref name=\"thelinkup\"/>\n\nAround the end of March 2015, he and [[MoStack]] released their \"Westwood Crib Session\". In late May 2015, he released \"Lean & Bop\",<ref name=\"thelinkup\"/> which was streamed more than 10 million times in total on music platforms.<ref name=\"sound of\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34636509|title=BBC Sound Of 2016 longlist revealed|publisher=BBC News|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924204418/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34636509|archive-date=24 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Around this time, he also released a \"Daily Duppy\" for GRM Music, which he followed with his first mixtape, ''The 15th Day''.<ref name=\"thelinkup\"/>\n\nJallow released the single \"Friendly\" in 2016, which received a nomination at the 2016 MOBO Awards, as well as \"Playing Sports\", \"Liar Liar\" (remix) and \"Solo One\", the last of which appeared on the ''[[Brotherhood (2016 film)|Brotherhood]]'' soundtrack.<ref name=\"thelinkup\"/>\n\nIn 2017, he featured on [[Nines (rapper)|Nines]]\u2019 \"High Roller\", which featured on his album ''[[One Foot Out]]''. He also featured on [[Stormzy]]'s \"Bad Boys\" from his album ''[[Gang Signs & Prayer]]'', which peaked at number 22 on the [[UK Singles Chart]],<ref name=\"bad boys\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/51166/stormzy-ft-ghetts-and-j-hus/|title=STORMZY FT GHETTS & J HUS|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=21 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322022822/http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/51166/stormzy-ft-ghetts-and-j-hus/|archive-date=22 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> on [[Dave (rapper)|Dave]]'s \"Samantha\", which peaked at number 63,<ref name=\"samantha\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/50839/dave-and-j-hus/|title=DAVE AND J HUS|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=21 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322021309/http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/50839/dave-and-j-hus/|archive-date=22 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and charted at number 9 with his solo composition \"Did You See\".<ref name=\"did you see\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48523/j-hus/|title=J HUS {{!}} full Official Chart History|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=20 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530131252/http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48523/j-hus/|archive-date=30 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The song served as the lead single off his debut album, ''[[Common Sense (J Hus album)|Common Sense]]'' (2017). Upon release, the album was positively received by fans, and includes features from Mo Stack, MIST, Tiggs da Author and [[Burna Boy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/04/03/j-hus-common-sense/ |title=J Hus Announced Details Of His Debut Album, Common Sense |publisher=Fader |date=4 April 2017 |accessdate=4 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404024620/http://www.thefader.com/2017/04/03/j-hus-common-sense |archive-date=4 April 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2018, he released his [[Extended play|EP]], ''[[Big Spang]]'' (2018)''.\n\nFollowing his arrest for carrying a bladed article in public, Jallow was sentenced to eight months in prison.<ref name=\":0\" /> Jallow's label stopped releasing music with his only verse whilst incarcerated coming from collaborator Dave's debut album, ''Psychodrama''<nowiki/>'s song \"Disaster.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/43688/1/dave-rapper-psychodrama-debut-album-therapy-mental-health|title=The radical healing sound of Dave\u2019s debut album Psychodrama|last=Dazed|date=13 March 2019|website=Dazed|language=en|access-date=20 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406015839/https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/43688/1/dave-rapper-psychodrama-debut-album-therapy-mental-health|archive-date=6 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Disaster\" debuted at number eight on the UK Singles Chart on 15 March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/dave-s-psychodrama-debuts-at-number-1-in-incredibly-close-official-albums-chart-battle-against-foals__25810/|title=Dave\u2019s Psychodrama album debuts at Number 1|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=20 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405225324/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/dave-s-psychodrama-debuts-at-number-1-in-incredibly-close-official-albums-chart-battle-against-foals__25810/|archive-date=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHours after his release from prison in April 2019 he made a surprise appearance on stage at [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]'s concert in London.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8505915/j-hus-drake-london-concert-prison-release|title=J Hus Hits the Stage at Drake's London Concert Just Hours After Release From Prison|website=www.billboard.com|language=en|access-date=6 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406115239/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8505915/j-hus-drake-london-concert-prison-release|archive-date=6 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, J Hus announced he will no longer tour for \"the next 3/4 years, maybe more\". He also stated that following his next album, he would have no more features but that he wanted to work with [[Burna Boy]] and [[21 Savage]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/j-hus-bombshell-rapper-announces-21031818|title=J Hus bombshell as rapper announces retirement \u2013 \u2018I\u2019ll never tour again\u2019|last=Domachowski|first=Lucy|date=2019-12-05|website=mirror|access-date=2019-12-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208162729/https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/j-hus-bombshell-rapper-announces-21031818|archive-date=8 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Legal issues ==\nIn 2011, J Hus was arrested outside Westfield following a \"mass attack\" on four people, which ended in one of them being stabbed. He'd already received a referral order that year after being caught with a knife in public.<ref>{{cite web |title=J Hus: Why he felt he had to take a knife to Westfield |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-46578742 |website=[[The BBC]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=16 December 2018 |date=15 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216050114/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-46578742 |archive-date=16 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 and 2015, he was arrested and served stints in Her Majesty's [[Feltham Prison]].<ref name=\"TheGuardian\" /> He accrued six convictions for ten offences between 2011 and 2016, including for carrying a knife and for violent disorder. He has also been given an [[ASBO]].<ref name=\"bbc2018\"/>\n\nIn September 2015 the musician was admitted to hospital after being stabbed five times in London.<ref name=\"vice\">{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/londons-new-afrobeat-trap-rap-sound|title=J Hus is Carving Out a New British Sound, Injecting UK Afrobeats with Rudeboy Flavour|publisher=Noisey|access-date=21 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314195934/https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/londons-new-afrobeat-trap-rap-sound|archive-date=14 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Whilst in hospital, he was criticised for posting on Instagram a photo of him making a gang sign from his hospital bed with the message \"5 stab wounds could never stop me #AntiCh #F***DaOvaSide\".<ref name=\"standard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/up-and-coming-london-rapper-makes-gang-signs-from-hospital-bed-after-being-stabbed-a2928626.html|title=Stabbed London rapped J Hus slammed for making 'gang signs' in hospital bed|publisher=[[Evening Standard]]|access-date=5 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706004537/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/up-and-coming-london-rapper-makes-gang-signs-from-hospital-bed-after-being-stabbed-a2928626.html|archive-date=6 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rowlands|first1=Geoffrey|title=J Hus on learning from his 2015 stabbing and maturing as a performer|url=http://www2.gulf-times.com/story/551477/J-Hus-on-learning-from-his-2015-stabbing-and-matur|website=Gulf Times|publisher=GPPC|accessdate=27 May 2018|date=29 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180520064403/http://www.gulf-times.com/story/551477/J-Hus-on-learning-from-his-2015-stabbing-and-matur|archive-date=20 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The attack left him with mild [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]], for which at the time of his 2018 imprisonment he was seeing a therapist.<ref name=\"bbc2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-46523489|title=J Hus jailed for eight months for carrying knife|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=14 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214152632/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-46523489|archive-date=14 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, he was arrested in Stratford and charged with [[Knife legislation#United Kingdom|carrying a knife in public]].<ref name=\"newham recorder\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newhamrecorder.co.uk/news/crime-court/rapper-j-hus-charged-with-possession-of-a-knife-near-westfield-shopping-centre-in-stratford-1-5575916|publisher=[[Newham Recorder]]|last1=Horton|first1=Tom|title=Rapper J Hus charged with possession of a knife near Westfield shopping centre|accessdate=5 July 2018|date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706022230/http://www.newhamrecorder.co.uk/news/crime-court/rapper-j-hus-charged-with-possession-of-a-knife-near-westfield-shopping-centre-in-stratford-1-5575916|archive-date=6 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He was subsequently dropped from the performance lineups of the [[TRNSMT]] and [[Wireless Festival|Wireless]] festivals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/07/04/j-hus-apologises-replaced-wireless-lineup-following-weapons-arrest-7682558.html|title=J Hus apologises as he\u2019s replaced on Wireless lineup following weapons arrest|last1=Evans|first1=Mel|publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|accessdate=4 July 2018|date=4 July 2018}}</ref> Jallow appeared at [[Thames Magistrates' Court]] on 22 June and was released on [[bail]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-44717815|title=J Hus thanks fans after arrest|date=4 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=11 December 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918145204/https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-44717815|archive-date=18 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 20 July, he pleaded not guilty,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rapper J Hus to go on trial after denying knife possession charge |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jul/20/rapper-j-hus-trial-denying-knife-possession-charge |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |accessdate=11 December 2018 |date=20 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214213947/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jul/20/rapper-j-hus-trial-denying-knife-possession-charge |archive-date=14 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> but changed his plea in October and in December was sentenced to eight months in jail.<ref name=\"bbc2018\"/> When asked why he had been carrying a six-inch blade, J Hus said: \"You know, it's [[Westfield Stratford City|Westfield]].\"<ref>{{cite web |title=J Hus: Why he felt he had to take a knife to Westfield |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-46578742 |website=[[The BBC]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=16 December 2018 |date=15 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216050114/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-46578742 |archive-date=16 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe was eventually released on 5 April 2019.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/dec/14/j-hus-jail-knife|title=Rapper J Hus sentenced to eight months in jail for carrying a knife|last=Snapes|first=Laura|date=14 December 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=20 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320214759/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/dec/14/j-hus-jail-knife|archive-date=20 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n=== Studio albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums, showing release date, label, formats, chart positions and certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Certifications \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Albums Char